dge-Ventures-Investment-Space|title=Deep Knowledge Ventures Makes First Investment in Space |website=Business Wire|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nPart of Transplanetary's activities include SPOCK (Space Program Ontologically Computed Knowledge),{{Better source needed example|date=April 2020|reason=A \"transplanetary\" corporation with a program called SPOCK?  I didn't find any reliable source but it seems a joke.|importance=}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.executivebiz.com/2014/09/deep-knowledge-ventures-to-fund-transplanetary-for-ai-space-program/|title=Deep Knowledge Ventures to Fund Transplanetary for AI, Space Program|newspaper=ExecutiveBiz|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> a machine learning program that claims to  use real-time analysis of trends in the space industry to make investment recommendations. The system analyzes publicly available data on commercial space companies, government space agencies, NGOs and academic research labs. The data that SPOCK develops then feeds into a roadmap of space exploration and settlement, attempting to enable investors to identify optimum investment targets, analysts to monitor industry growth and industry professionals to target supply chain partners.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://oemcapital.com/2014/09/deep-knowledge-ventures-acquired-transplanetary-corporation/|title=Deep Knowledge Ventures acquired Transplanetary Corporation |newspaper=Technology Investment Banking|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Deep Knowledge Ventures incorporated a subsidiary investment fund, Deep Knowledge Life Sciences (DKLS), a London-based venture fund focused on disruptive [[biopharmaceutical]], [[Precision medicine|precision medicin]]<nowiki/>e, and AI healthcare companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deepknowledge.life/|title=DeepKnowledge.Life Sciences|website=www.deepknowledge.life|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDKLS's portfolio companies including [[Insilico Medicine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://insilicomedic